<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from St John Ambulance (UEC0003)</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 12pt 0pt 0pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="458" height="211" alt="" style="margin-left:126pt; margin-top:349.1pt; position:absolute; z-index:0" /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Scope of evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">St John Ambulance (SJA) welcomes the Health Committee’s invitation to provide submissions before its examination of Sir Bruce Keogh’s review and the winter performance of emergency and urgent care services.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">SJA is the nation’s leading first aid charity. In England, it provides a range of services to NHS ambulance and hospital trusts. It also works closely with category 1 responders as recognised by the Civil Contingencies Act 2004.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our comments relate to chapter 3 of the Keogh review, and observations based on our experience in supporting the NHS and other statutory services during times of community hardship.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The role of independent providers (including the voluntary sector)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The proposed model for emergency care (Keogh report, p. 23) shows the voluntary sector as a specific partner for self-care. This is partly to indicate that the sector is invited to help develop new options for self-care (ibid, p. 22). However, it could be inferred from this table that the sector would be limited to these activities.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In fact, the voluntary sector is currently involved throughout the system. In the case of SJA, this is done by, for example, providing community first responder (CFA) schemes, plus ambulance services that bring patients into A&amp;E, both on behalf of ambulance service trusts or through the provision of first aid at public events. Under the Keogh recommendations, we would expect to continue a role bringing patients to primary care centres (or other primary care providers), emergency and major emergency centres.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Much of SJA’s ambulance service work is similar to that provided by other voluntary or private organisations. In times of community difficulty, ambulance trusts will engage with both voluntary and private organisations. Voluntary organisations such as SJA will also have built up relationships with category 1 responders and will, in line with pre-agreed scenario plans, put their resources behind wider community support should the need arise.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Support during the current winter period (2013/2014)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">SJA’s additional support can be broken down into day-to-day support to ambulance trusts, and civil contingency support. Arrangements vary dependent on the type of work being carried out and the resources required. The personnel involved are equipped to standards appropriate for the role they are carrying out. They may be volunteers or employees. Work may be charged for (with any surplus being ploughed back into the charity), provided on a cost-recovery basis, carried out free of charge.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All ten ambulance service trusts have requested additional vehicles and crews from SJA to deal with increased demand. Where possible we have met these requests.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Civil emergency requirements have differed from region to region. For example, support in the south east region alone has included:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dozens of first aiders on standby to provide first aid support at rest centres where evacuated people can stay for up to 72 hours</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">SJA volunteers as call handlers helping with tactical communications and emergency response</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Advice and liaison at local and national level</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Immediate care and medical assessment provided to people in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Yalding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who had missed evacuation calls</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Assessment of residents at a secure care centre of 180 vulnerable adults who could not be evacuated</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Involvement with the phased return of residents, supporting responders and the local community and backfilling the statutory ambulance provision.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The need to plan</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The requirements of the Care Quality Commission, the imperative to make the most use of charitable assets, modern fleet management procedures and the establishment of Clinical Commissioning Groups mean that our ambulances and other resources are now managed on a regional basis.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">When deciding what resources to invest in, we prioritise vehicles and equipment that will be used most frequently. A business case proposing the purchase of a vehicle or specialist equipment that is likely to be used only once or twice a year is unlikely to be regarded as a prudent use of charitable resources.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Thus, for example, our national fleet includes bariatric ambulances (for specialist patient transport services) and 4X4 vehicles (for first aid services at certain public events). It follows that over time the nature of our ambulance fleet (and the fleet of other similar organisations) may change and this must be borne in mind by those involved with civil contingency planning. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Equally, during the winter, requests from additional support for A&amp;E and civil contingency work (as detailed above in paragraphs 8-9) are met from a single pool of resources. Any A&amp;E planning that does not take into account the potential need for civil contingency support to communities will be found wanting.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">One way in which the pool of volunteers could be increased would be an expansion of CFR schemes. Members of the Health Committee have previously noted the effectiveness of such schemes. Although CFR units involve a rota system, those not on call can be mobilised during times of emergency subject to their other commitments (including employment commitments). </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">SJA has wide experience in partnering with ambulance services to develop CFR schemes and would be pleased to discuss its experiences with the Committee or indeed the DoH and NHS management teams.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>